Anne Taylor’s weekly CAMPUS NOTES column on
page eight carries a head set in ST. CLAIR type face.
ST. CLAIR _ sometimes known as “circus type”
_ became popular in the Midwestern United States
around 1875 and is usually used only for headlines; it
“has a grey direct in mass use,” according lo a typographers’ handbook or the period.
The new head this week on PERSONALS (also
page eight) is set in KISMET, designed by Boston
printer John jumping in 1879. Horace Gi‘kelly’s New
York WEEKLY TRIBUNE eventually used this type
iooe for its Personals column late in the century.
LETI‘ERS TO THE EDITOR and NEWS BRIEFS
step (that is, standing) heads on our editorial pages
are set in ALFERTA — perhaps the most interesting
of classic American type styles.
ALFERTA displays a deﬁsite exotic inﬂhence
with Spanish ringtones; it was designed by w. F.
maintains in 1351.
maintains went to Chicago following the Great Fire,
and ellis lace developed — it is said ~— mm the visit
compensation he read by the (tree‘s witnesses.
ALFERTA can “heat a display,” one modern type
book claims.
