JONES ON JONES
(Editor’s Note: The following is him Jones' here
soon! account of the events
that led to his arrest last
year.)
LIBERATION NEWS
SERVICE
After midnight on July 14,
1967, l and my conditions
were driving in my station Wa'
inn, talking and listening to the
radio. As we reached the corner of South Orange Ave, which
was on our direct route home,
we were stopped by at least two
cartoons of white-selected police with shotguns and several
objectives. They advanced on
our van; we thought that at
most they would check us out,
ask ibm identiﬁnations, etc,
then let us go.
We were told to come out of
the car. When i opened the
door and stopped down, one detective, whom i recognized as
having once attended Harrigget High School while i was
there, reached up to me,
streaming that "we were the
bastards" who had been shooting at them. “Yes," he said.
“a blue panel truck." (My
station wagon is an olive-green
career bus.) I said that we
had not been shooting at anyone. I told the officer that I
thought i remembered him
from high school — whereupon
he hit me in the face and three
me up against the side of the
truck. (The others had also
been taken from the truck.)
The detective then began to
tab me as hard as he could
with his postal in my stomach,
asking, “Where are the guns?"
I told him there were no guns.
Suddenly it seemed that five
or six of the officers surrounded me and began to beat me.
i was hit perhaps live times
on top of my head by nightsticks, and when I tell, some of
the officers Went about periodically trying to break my
hands, allows and providers.
One officer tried to kick me in
the grown — and there were
many patches thrown. As they
beat, they kept calling me,
"Animal,” and asking me,
“Where are the guns?” Inside
the wagon, the heating continued. They took us from the
wagon and as I was pushed
up the states at Police Headquarters, an officer called out,
"Wait a minute,” then reached
me in the pit of the stomach.
I fell to the ground switching
my stomach.
Inside the station, Mr. Spfna
(the Police Director) was
standing behind the desk. I
asked him had he ordered me
better. He replied, “They got
you, didn't they?” — sailing.
An officer then granted me,
asked me to take off my belt.
He ran his hand in my pocket,
pulling out my wallet . . . later
I discovered that the officer
had taken about $65.00 and I
guestbook out of the wallet.
We were taken to City los
vital; i was changed in and
handcuffed in a wheelchair.
The “doctors" put in eight or
nine switches. (At no time were
we allowed to make a phone
call. At no time were we read
our rights.)
We were then taken to police
headquarters on Franklin St.,
iingerpdnted and brought into
the countries and arraigned.
The protection asked for $25.000 mail for me, which the judge
allowed. I was taken to Essex
County jail and put into military
requirement, where i remained
until I was released. (All options for covering the mail were
denied.)
