By
Wm. F. BUCKLEY, Jr.
You will have noticed that Mr. Clark Clifford, our forthcoming
Secretary of Defense, has been com on the question whether he in
a hawk or ii love, containing, as he put it, “such ornithological
categories." But the wisemen in Washington tell us that he is Com
viewed of the lightning of the Vietnam war, and indeed it is on:
likely that President Johnson would have appointed to sit at all
left hand someone who substantially disturbed with him on so important a question. It has even been whispered that Mr. Clifford
will pursue the objectives of victory in Vietnam more wholeheartedly than Mr. McNamara did, about whom the insider: tell of
great providing over the entire matter, an providing which cannon compare with the providing of American soldiers as they hear
skills drop over them which were manufactured in the Soviet
Union and found their way to the war front because Mr. McNamara — and Mr. Johnson -— agnnlze over world opinion.
But let us assume that the conduct of the Vietnam war will
proceed more or less at the pace or the last year or two, and hope
that the cumulative treasures on North Vietnam will begin to tell.
and that before long the military creating and training will state.
What then? What; will we see after it is over in Vietnam? A period
of peace in the Southeast Asian part of the world we are entitled to
expect.
But history teaches us the unlikelihood that there will be peace
everywhere in the world. And all the less likely considering the
techniques of the modern revolutionists, who have learned to cause
so much disturbance with so few men.
The qty-called wars of generation are certain to prove to be lit.
military Model A Ford of the 20th Century — cheap, durable, and
ubiquitous. All It takes is a couple of thousand guerrillas. I pipeline to the soviet union, a local the Guevara, and you are in
business. Inasmuch as the United States is primarily charged with
the responsibilities of counteraction, it is we who need to think beyond the Vietnam war and ask ourselves whether we are willing
again in pay so laugh - price as we will have paid in Vietnam in
order to contain other national generation prints in other parts of
the world.
Mr. Clifford should turn his attention to the problem, and surely the place to start would be by accounting a future commitment
to the volunteer army. If you like, to the secretary army. The
arguments in favor of it have been frequently rehearsed, as recently as in 1964 by both the presidential candidates. As is so often
the case with election year promises, nothing has been done, nothing in this case to phase out the draft. Perhaps the reason why is
the great manpower demands of the Vietnam war. But that is no
reason for putting off a public discussion of the volunteer military,
and it is always appropriate to bigthink about strategic matters
upon taking the path of notice.
The conventional arguments are that, e) a professional force
readers professional services. As things now stand, an American
technician becomes highly qualified, highly useful. by let us say
June, and in September his tour of duty is over. b) The extra cost
or during men into a professional military force is not likely to
exceed the great cost of continually training the millions of young
men whose services are used over so short a period. To which conventional argument should he added, {1) the great condition
caused by a draft, and the influence Of that condition on the
circulation of an effective foreign policy backed up by a mobile
armed force. ii the United States is going to help out next year in
Brazil, the year after in the Sudan, and the year after that in Nigeria, surely we do nor want to really the pensions of the existing
war? it is bad enough to concentrate another haltrcentury of financing resistance to the columnists throughout the world, but it
is more than flesh and blood can bear to concentrate a Slyyear
old weight Macdonald relating ills 25th consecutive invitation to
the White House.
The influence of American youth and their episode. the inlelieciuais, the academicians, the opinion-makers, the noisemakers,
on foreign policy is considerable, and in some ways healthy. Their
investigation to go and fight in these chubby wars in chubby parts
of life \world is altogether understandable. But until we simply
give up on the rest of the world, we have got to help out. And the
way to do that is primarily by making arms available, and also
small, professional forces which will absorb the Shock until such
moment as the locale are trained to attend to their own defense.
Perhaps someone in Washington will be good enough to question Mr. Clifford on the matter at his next press conference.
 
