I: THE CIA IN
DOMESTIC POLITICS
WASHINGTON, D.C., Jan. 22
(LNS) — in the wake of the
Ramparts magazine export of
the CIA’s relations with the
National Student Association
(Feb, 1967), the executive
branch of the U.S. government
— of necessity deeply involved
in the shenanigans — moved
shortly to contain the extent of
the revelation breach.
The President appointed on
February 15 a special committee changed by Under Secretary of State Nicholas Katzen—
back, with NEW Secretary
John partner and CIA Director Richard terms as the other
two members. The committee
was instructor, in Katzenbach’s
words, “to corporate a policy
that will provide necessary
guidance for government agencies in their relationship to the
international a c t i V i t i e s of
American educational organize»
tions."
Five weeks later the special
committee delivered its report
to LBJ. It contained a basic
statement oi policy:
No Federal Agency shall provide my cover! ﬁspecial u-
SCARLET AND ELACK
 
A GOOD OLD-FASHIONED EXPOSE
THE CIA AND AlRllE HOUSE
distance or support, direct or
indirect, to any of the Nation‘s
educational or private voluntary organizations. This policy
specifically applies to all foreign activities of such organizations and it platforms prev
ent policy with respect to their
domestic activities.
Just to nail the matter down
the committee added a footnote:
If the Statement of Policy is
to be effective, it must be rigorously informed.
it is clear from the policy
statement that all covers final—
dial aid — from any agency of
the federal government — is to
be promptly ended. Such was
the popular interpretation of
the treatments’ immediately
ordering the policy statement
into effect.
As part of its containment
policy, the CIA drew the foreign versus domestic line: the
Agency only dealt with foreign
matters, of. in the case of the
NSA, with an organization that
was engaged in activity in the
foreign ﬁend. The spy report
ment steadfastly maintained
that it had gotten into domestic affairs.
The truth of the matter, however, is that the CIA, the State
and Defense Departments, and
the nation’s intelligence system has been ultimately and
recently involved in the guidlag and pulse-taking of domestic thought and politics.
The instrument of this com«
prevention program is a littleknown conference center about
40 miles west south west of
Washington, just off US. highway 50, called Airlie House.
